2 Usque quo : ut quid. The rude and literal style of the Old Latin meets us now to the end of c. 64. Hence such phrases as usque quo z ἕως τίνος ; ut quid ἶ ἵνα τί in this quotation. Elsewhere, a modo = ἀπὸ τοῦ νῦν ; si as direct interrogative = εἰ. Many such combinations of preposition and adverb, or of two prepositions live on in Freneh, demaiu from de mane (Ruth ii, 7, de mane usque nune), dcrrlere from a'e retro, (teliors from deforis, etc.‚ etc.
